ReplicaSet Vs StatefulSet Vs Deployment (Video - 1:50

Deployments manage standard, stateless apps.
StatefulSets manage apps that need unique identities and saved data.
ReplicaSets keep a set number of identical Pods running.

Quick Comparison

Feature                    ReplicaSet                          Deployment                              StatefulSet
Main Use                   Basic scaling                       Stateless apps                          Stateful apps
Pod Names                  Random suffixes                     Random suffixes                         Fixed index numbers
Storage                    Shared volume                       Shared volume                           Unique volume per Pod
Rollouts                   Manual updates                      Automated rollouts                      Careful, ordered updates

1. ReplicaSet

A ReplicaSet ensures that a specific number of Pods are running at the same time. It is a simple tool that watches your cluster and 
starts or stops Pods to match your target number. You rarely create ReplicaSets directly. Instead, you use Deployments to manage them for
you.

Best for: Ensuring basic app uptime.
Pod Identity: Every Pod is identical and interchangeable.
Example: Running three copies of a simple web page.

2. Deployment

A Deployment is a higher-level tool that controls ReplicaSets. It lets you update your app to a new version without downtime. If an 
update fails, the Deployment can automatically roll back to the old version. It is the most common way to deploy stateless apps.

Best for: Web servers, APIs, and stateless apps.
Key Feature: Easy, automated app updates.
Example: Hosting an online store front-end that saves no local data.

3. StatefulSet

A StatefulSet manages apps that require a unique identity or persistent storage. Unlike standard Pods, these Pods are not interchangeable.
They are created in a strict order (0, 1, 2) and keep their exact same name and storage disk even if they restart.

Best for: Databases and clustered apps.
Key Feature: Unique storage and fixed network IDs for each Pod.
Example: Running databases like MySQL, PostgreSQL, or MongoDB.

Labels and Selectors (Video - 1:52
Labels and selectors are key-value pairs that Kubernetes uses to group and filter resources. Labels are tags attached to resources, and
selectors are queries used to find those tags.

What are Labels?

Labels are metadata tags attached to Kubernetes objects like Pods. They do not change how the Pod runs. Instead, they help organize your 
system.

Key-value format: Written as key: value (for example, environment: production).
Flexible naming: You can choose any names that make sense to your team.
Common uses: Marking app names, release versions, or team ownership.

What are Selectors?

Selectors are filters used to look up objects based on their labels. Since Kubernetes resources are loosely linked, one resource finds 
another by matching labels.

Equality-based: Finds exact matches, like environment == production.
Set-based: Finds a range of matches, like environment in (production, staging).

How They Work Together (YAML Example)
This example shows how a Service uses a selector to find and route traffic to a specific Pod.

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: web-pod
  labels:                  # 🏷️ Attached Label
    app: frontend
    env: production
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: web-service
spec:
  selector:                # 🔍 Selector Query
    app: frontend          # Finds the Pod with the matching label
  ports:
  - protocol: TCP
    port: 80
    targetPort: 80

Why Use Labels and Selectors?

Traffic Routing: Services use selectors to send user traffic to the correct backend Pods.
Controller Tracking: Deployments use selectors to know which ReplicaSets and Pods they are responsible for managing.
Easy Searching: Developers can filter cluster resources quickly using commands like kubectl get pods -l env=production.

Rolling Update in Deployment (Video - 1:57 - 2:04)

A rolling update is the default way Kubernetes updates an application inside a Deployment. It replaces old Pods with new ones gradually,
ensuring your app has zero downtime during the update.

How It Works
Instead of taking down the entire application at once, a rolling update changes your setup step-by-step:

Starts New Pods: Kubernetes creates a new Pod using your updated container image.
Checks Health: It waits for the new Pod to become healthy and ready to take traffic.
Terminates Old Pods: Once the new Pod is ready, Kubernetes shuts down an old Pod.
Repeats: This process continues until all Pods are running the new version.

The Two Key Controls

You can fine-tune exactly how fast or slow this update happens by adding two settings to your manifest spec.strategy.rollingUpdate:

maxSurge: The maximum number of extra Pods Kubernetes can create above your target number during the update. For example, if you want 4
Pods and set this to 1, Kubernetes can temporarily run 5 Pods.

maxUnavailable: The maximum number of Pods that can be offline or broken during the update process. For example, if you want 4 Pods and 
set this to 1, Kubernetes ensures at least 3 Pods are always running.

You can set these options using whole numbers (like 1) or percentages (like 25%).

YAML Manifest ExampleHere is a Deployment manifest configured to perform a controlled rolling update:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: my-web-app
spec:
  replicas: 4
  strategy:
    type: RollingUpdate
    rollingUpdate:
      maxSurge: 1          # Max 1 extra Pod allowed during update
      maxUnavailable: 0    # Never let any Pods go down during update
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: web
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: web
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: nginx
        image: nginx:1.25.1 # Changing this version triggers the update
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80

Useful Commands

You can manage and monitor your rolling updates from the command line:

Trigger an update: kubectl set image deployment/my-web-app nginx=nginx:1.25.2
Check status: kubectl rollout status deployment/my-web-app
Undo a mistake: kubectl rollout undo deployment/my-web-app

ReplicaSet (Video -  2:04 - 2:06)

A ReplicaSet is a core Kubernetes resource that ensures a specific number of identical Pods are running at all times. If a Pod crashes, 
gets deleted, or the underlying node fails, the ReplicaSet automatically spots the issue and starts a new Pod to replace it.

Core Functions

Redundancy: It keeps multiple copies of your app running to handle user traffic.
Scale: It lets you easily increase or decrease the number of running Pods.
Self-Healing: It replaces failed or deleted Pods automatically to maintain uptime.

YAML Manifest Example

While you rarely create ReplicaSets directly in production, here is what a basic manifest looks like:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: ReplicaSet
metadata:
  name: frontend-replicaset
spec:
  replicas: 3             # 🎯 Target number of Pods to keep running
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      tier: frontend      # 🔍 Finds Pods with this label
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        tier: frontend    # 🏷️ Label given to new Pods it creates
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: php-redis
        image: gcr.io/google_samples/gb-frontend:v3

How a ReplicaSet Decides What to Manage

A ReplicaSet uses labels and selectors to manage Pods. It does not actually own the Pods it creates. Instead, it constantly searches the
cluster for any Pods that match its spec.selector.

Too few Pods: If it finds fewer matching Pods than the replicas count, it launches new ones using the template.

Too many Pods: If you manually create an extra Pod with the exact same label, the ReplicaSet will delete it to match the target number.

ReplicaSet vs. Deployment
In real-world setups, you should almost always use a Deployment instead of a raw ReplicaSet.

ReplicaSets only manage the number of Pods. They do not know how to safely update container images to new versions.
Deployments manage ReplicaSets automatically. When you change an image version, a Deployment creates a new ReplicaSet and performs a
smooth rolling update for you.

Daemon Sets (Video 2:07 - 2:12)

A DaemonSet is a special Kubernetes resource that ensures a single copy of a specific Pod runs on every single worker node in your 
cluster. When you add a new node to the cluster, the DaemonSet automatically adds the Pod to it. If you remove a node, the Pod is 
removed too.

Core Functions

Total Coverage: It automatically deploys exactly one Pod per node across the cluster.
Auto-Scaling: It senses when the cluster grows or shrinks and adjusts Pods automatically.
Infrastructure Focused: It is mostly used for background system tools rather than user-facing apps.

Common Use Cases
Unlike Deployments that balance app traffic, DaemonSets are perfect for local node tools:

Log Collection: Running a tool like Fluentd or Logstash on every node to gather system logs.
Node Monitoring: Running agents like Prometheus Node Exporter to track CPU and memory health.
Cluster Networking: Running network plug-ins like Calico or Flannel to manage cluster traffic.

YAML Manifest Example
Here is a basic manifest file for a DaemonSet that runs a logging tool:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: DaemonSet
metadata:
  name: fluentd-elasticsearch
spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      name: fluentd-logging
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        name: fluentd-logging
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: fluentd-elasticsearch
        image: quay.io/fluentd_elasticsearch/fluentd:v2.5.2
